3 Reasons to <strong>NOT</strong> Document Your Code
1. Clients don't pay for comments<br><em>they pay for code that RUNS</em>.
Comments aren't (just) for clients, they're for you.
2. It's just a temporary fix.
Is it in the repo? It's not temporary.
3. I'm the only one who's going to be working on this.
I can't remember why I wrote something 6 <del>months</del><ins>weeks</ins> ago.
<ul><li><a href="https://make.wordpress.org/core/handbook/best-practices/inline-documentation-standards/">https://make.wordpress.org/core/handbook/best-practices/inline-documentation-standards/</a></li><li><a href="https://css-tricks.com/the-art-of-comments/">https://css-tricks.com/the-art-of-comments/</a></li></ul>
Bonus: I know exactly how every function arg works.
I can't ever remember the exact args for many functions. Let your IDE read comments and provide hints.
